### 3. CATS OAM Framework
* **Presenter**: Juan Deng
* **Slides**: [2.2-draft-ietf-cats-oam-fw](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-cats-slides-for-draft-ietf-cats-oam-fw-00)
* **Draft**: `draft-ietf-cats-oam-fw`
* **Discussion**:
  * Juan Deng presented updates to the OAM framework (revisions up to -01), which included removing "SI-OAM" and "SVC-OAM" terminologies, adding push/pull reporting modes, clarifying problem statements/gaps, refining the 4-layer OAM model (Service OAM, Instance OAM, Path OAM, Link OAM), and detailing security and deployment considerations.
  * *Q&A*:
    * Luis M. Contreras asked whether it would be simpler to run an OAM probe in the virtualization environment collocated with the service instance rather than imposing requirements directly on the service instance itself. Juan Deng agreed that OAM should monitor metrics reports rather than looking inside the service instance itself.
    * Sheng Li commented that the draft currently lacks sufficient CATS-specific content and should incorporate more dedicated CATS text in future updates. Juan Deng agreed to clarify these aspects.
    * Boris Khasanov asked (via microphone and chat) why STAMP was not considered as an OAM tool alongside TWAMP or BFD. Juan Deng replied that existing measurement tools could be extended to support computing metrics and service instances.
    * *Chat Discussion*: Carolina Caeiro queried the definition of "Multi-Domain Fault Isolation" and whether TRACE mode is strictly intra-domain. Quan Xiong clarified that this refers to fault localization across AS domains or areas within an administrative domain. Adrian Farrel pointed out that sharing fault details across separate AS domains is atypical and suggested focusing on failure location between CATS-forwarders and service instances without emphasizing administrative boundaries. Carolina Caeiro noted that inter-domain operations might be outside the current charter scope.

